                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "UGAz6",
                      "fill": "$text-muted",
                      "content": "2026-03-24",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "rectangle",
              "id": "6oNAj",
              "name": "sep",
              "fill": "$border-default",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "height": 1
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "A4gQm",
              "fill": "$text-body",
              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "content": "In the rapidly evolving landscape of AI, many have questioned whether Retrieval-Augmented Generation remains relevant in an era of ever-expanding context windows. The answer, perhaps surprisingly, is a resounding yes — but not for the reasons most people think.",
              "lineHeight": 1.8,
              "fontFamily": "Inter",
              "fontSize": 15,
              "fontWeight": "normal"
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "ogxh9",
              "name": "hlBlock",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "fill": "#3B82F60D",
              "cornerRadius": "$radius-sm",
              "stroke": {
                "thickness": 1,
                "fill": "#3B82F626"
              },
              "layout": "vertical",
              "padding": [
                12,
                16
              ],
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "Fx2C5",
                  "fill": "$text-body",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The key insight is that retrieval doesn't replace generation — it grounds it. Without retrieval, LLMs hallucinate. With retrieval, they become reliable knowledge workers.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.8,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 15,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "e8zVe",
              "fill": "$text-body",
              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "content": "This distinction matters enormously in production systems. When your AI assistant needs to reference company documentation, customer records, or regulatory guidelines, you cannot afford hallucination. RAG provides the factual backbone that makes LLM outputs trustworthy.",
              "lineHeight": 1.8,
              "fontFamily": "Inter",
              "fontSize": 15,
              "fontWeight": "normal"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "bihw0",
              "fill": "$text-body",
              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "content": "Furthermore, even with million-token context windows, the economics of stuffing everything into context are prohibitive. RAG acts as an intelligent filter — bringing only the most relevant fragments into the generation window.",
              "lineHeight": 1.8,
              "fontFamily": "Inter",
              "fontSize": 15,
              "fontWeight": "normal"
            }
          ]
        },
